[src:dex-language/array-programming] The previous statements are also valid MATLAB expressions if the third one is executed before the others (numerical comparisons may be false because of round-off errors).
[src:dex-language/array-programming] However, these solutions are neither the most concise ones (e.g. still remains the need to notationally differentiate overdetermined systems) nor the most computationally efficient.
[src:dex-language/array-programming] The latter point is easy to understand when considering again the scalar equivalent `a * x = b`, for which the solution `x = a^-1 * b` would require two operations instead of the more efficient `x = b / a`.
[src:dex-language/array-programming] This is not only an example of terse array programming from the coding point of view but also from the computational efficiency perspective, which in several array programming languages benefits from quite efficient linear algebra libraries such as ATLAS or LAPACK.
[src:dex-language/array-programming] The use of specialized and efficient libraries to provide more terse abstractions is also common in other programming languages.
[src:dex-language/array-programming] In C++ several linear algebra libraries exploit the language's ability to overload operators.
[src:dex-language/array-programming] In some cases a very terse abstraction in those languages is explicitly influenced by the array programming paradigm, as the NumPy extension library to Python, Armadillo and Blitz++ libraries do.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation is a subtle and central tool to automatize the simultaneous computation of the numerical values of arbitrarily complex functions and their derivatives with no need for the symbolic representation of the derivative; only the function rule or an algorithm thereof is required.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Auto-differentiation is thus neither numeric nor symbolic, nor is it a combination of both.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In contrast to the more traditional numerical methods based on finite differences, auto-differentiation is 'in theory' exact, and in comparison to symbolic algorithms, it is computationally inexpensive.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation exploits the fact that every computer calculation, no matter how complicated, executes a sequence of elementary arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, etc.) and elementary functions (exp, log, sin, cos, etc.).
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] By applying the chain rule repeatedly to these operations, partial derivatives of arbitrary order can be computed automatically, accurately to working precision, and using at most a small constant factor of more arithmetic operations than the original program.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation is distinct from symbolic differentiation and numerical differentiation.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Symbolic differentiation faces the difficulty of converting a computer program into a single mathematical expression and can lead to inefficient code.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Numerical differentiation (the method of finite differences) can introduce round-off errors in the discretization process and cancellation.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Both of these classical methods have problems with calculating higher derivatives, where complexity and errors increase.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Finally, both of these classical methods are slow at computing partial derivatives of a function with respect to *many* inputs, as is needed for gradient-based optimization algorithms.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation solves all of these problems.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Because of its efficiency and accuracy in computing first and higher order derivatives, auto-differentiation finds diverse applications in scientific computing and mathematics, and there are numerous computational implementations of auto-differentiation.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Among these, one mentions INTLAB, Sollya, and InCLosure.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In practice, there are two types (modes) of algorithmic differentiation: a forward-type and a reversed-type.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Presently, the two types are highly correlated and complementary and both have a wide variety of applications in, e.g., non-linear optimization, sensitivity analysis, robotics, machine learning, computer graphics, and computer vision.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Automatic differentiation is particularly important in the field of machine learning.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] For example, it allows one to implement backpropagation in a neural network without a manually-computed derivative.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Fundamental to automatic differentiation is the decomposition of differentials provided by the chain rule of partial derivatives of composite functions.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Usually, two distinct modes of automatic differentiation are presented.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The value of the partial derivative, called the *seed*, is propagated forward or backward and is initially ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial x}{\partial x}}=1}$ or ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial y}{\partial y}}=1}$ .
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Forward accumulation evaluates the function and calculates the derivative with respect to one independent variable in one pass.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In contrast, reverse accumulation requires the evaluated partial functions for the partial derivatives.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Reverse accumulation therefore evaluates the function first and calculates the derivatives with respect to all independent variables in an additional pass.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Which of these two types should be used depends on the sweep count.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The computational complexity of one sweep is proportional to the complexity of the original code.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Backpropagation of errors in multilayer perceptrons, a technique used in machine learning, is a special case of reverse accumulation.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Forward accumulation was introduced by R.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] According to Andreas Griewank, reverse accumulation has been suggested since the late 1960s, but the inventor is unknown.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Seppo Linnainmaa published reverse accumulation in 1976.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In forward accumulation AD, one first fixes the *independent variable* with respect to which differentiation is performed and computes the derivative of each sub-expression recursively.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Compared to reverse accumulation, forward accumulation is natural and easy to implement as the flow of derivative information coincides with the order of evaluation.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Each variable $w_{i}$ is augmented with its derivative ${\dot {w}}_{i}$ (stored as a numerical value, not a symbolic expression), ${\dot {w}}_{i}={\frac {\partial w_{i}}{\partial x}}$ as denoted by the dot.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The derivatives are then computed in sync with the evaluation steps and combined with other derivatives via the chain rule.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The choice of the independent variable to which differentiation is performed affects the *seed* values *ẇ*1 and *ẇ*2.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] With the seed values set, the values propagate using the chain rule as shown.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Figure 2 shows a pictorial depiction of this process as a computational graph.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Forward accumulation calculates the function and the derivative (but only for one independent variable each) in one pass.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The associated method call expects the expression Z to be derived with regard to a variable V.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The method returns a pair of the evaluated function and its derivative.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The method traverses the expression tree recursively until a variable is reached.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] If the derivative with respect to this variable is requested, its derivative is 1, 0 otherwise.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Then the partial function as well as the partial derivative are evaluated.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In reverse accumulation AD, the *dependent variable* to be differentiated is fixed and the derivative is computed *with respect to* each sub-expression recursively.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Reverse accumulation traverses the chain rule from outside to inside, or in the case of the computational graph in Figure 3, from top to bottom.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The example function is scalar-valued, and thus there is only one seed for the derivative computation, and only one sweep of the computational graph is needed to calculate the (two-component) gradient.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] This can be mitigated to some extent by storing only a subset of the intermediate variables and then reconstructing the necessary work variables by repeating the evaluations, a technique known as rematerialization.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Checkpointing is also used to save intermediary states.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The data flow graph of a computation can be manipulated to calculate the gradient of its original calculation.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] This is done by adding an adjoint node for each primal node, connected by adjoint edges which parallel the primal edges but flow in the opposite direction.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The nodes in the adjoint graph represent multiplication by the derivatives of the functions calculated by the nodes in the primal.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] For instance, addition in the primal causes fanout in the adjoint; fanout in the primal causes addition in the adjoint; a unary function *y* = *f*(*x*) in the primal causes *x̄* = *ȳ* *f*′(*x*) in the adjoint; etc.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Reverse accumulation requires two passes: In the forward pass, the function is evaluated first and the partial results are cached.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In the reverse pass, the partial derivatives are calculated and the previously derived value is back-propagated.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The corresponding method call expects the expression Z to be derived and *seeded* with the derived value of the parent expression.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] For the top expression, Z is differentiated with respect to Z, this is 1.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The method traverses the expression tree recursively until a variable is reached and adds the current *seed* value to the derivative expression.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Forward and reverse accumulation are just two (extreme) ways of traversing the chain rule.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The problem of computing a full Jacobian of *f* : ℝ*n* → ℝ*m* with a minimum number of arithmetic operations is known as the *optimal Jacobian accumulation* (OJA) problem, which is NP-complete.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Central to this proof is the idea that algebraic dependencies may exist between the local partials that label the edges of the graph.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In particular, two or more edge labels may be recognized as equal.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The complexity of the problem is still open if it is assumed that all edge labels are unique and algebraically independent.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Forward mode automatic differentiation is accomplished by augmenting the algebra of real numbers and obtaining a new arithmetic.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] An additional component is added to every number to represent the derivative of a function at the number, and all arithmetic operators are extended for the augmented algebra.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The augmented algebra is the algebra of dual numbers.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Replace every number $\,x$ with the number $x+x'\varepsilon$ , where $x'$ is a real number, but $\varepsilon$ is an abstract number with the property $\varepsilon ^{2}=0$ (an infinitesimal; see *Smooth infinitesimal analysis*).
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Now, polynomials can be calculated in this augmented arithmetic.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The new arithmetic consists of ordered pairs, elements written ${\textstyle \langle x,x'\rangle }$ , with ordinary arithmetics on the first component, and first order differentiation arithmetic on the second component, as described above.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] When a binary basic arithmetic operation is applied to mixed arguments—the pair ${\textstyle \langle u,u'\rangle }$ and the real number c —the real number is first lifted to ${\textstyle \langle c,0\rangle }$ .
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The derivative of a function ${\textstyle f:\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R} }$ at the point $x_{0}$ is now found by calculating ${\textstyle f(\langle x_{0},1\rangle )}$ using the above arithmetic, which gives ${\textstyle \langle f(x_{0}),f'(x_{0})\rangle }$ as the result.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] An example implementation based on the dual number approach follows.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Multivariate functions can be handled with the same efficiency and mechanisms as univariate functions by adopting a directional derivative operator.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] If all the elements of $\nabla f$ are desired, then n function evaluations are required.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Note that in many optimization applications, the directional derivative is indeed sufficient.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The above arithmetic can be generalized to calculate second order and higher derivatives of multivariate functions.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] However, the arithmetic rules quickly grow complicated: complexity is quadratic in the highest derivative degree.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Instead, truncated Taylor polynomial algebra can be used.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The resulting arithmetic, defined on generalized dual numbers, allows efficient computation using functions as if they were a data type.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Once the Taylor polynomial of a function is known, the derivatives are easily extracted.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Forward-mode AD is implemented by a nonstandard interpretation of the program in which real numbers are replaced by dual numbers, constants are lifted to dual numbers with a zero epsilon coefficient, and the numeric primitives are lifted to operate on dual numbers.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] This nonstandard interpretation is generally implemented using one of two strategies: *source code transformation* or *operator overloading*.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] The source code for a function is replaced by an automatically generated source code that includes statements for calculating the derivatives interleaved with the original instructions.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Source code transformation can be implemented for all programming languages, and it is also easier for the compiler to do compile time optimizations.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] However, the implementation of the AD tool itself is more difficult and the build system is more complex.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Operator overloading is a possibility for source code written in a language supporting it.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Objects for real numbers and elementary mathematical operations must be overloaded to cater for the augmented arithmetic depicted above.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] This requires no change in the form or sequence of operations in the original source code for the function to be differentiated, but often requires changes in basic data types for numbers and vectors to support overloading and often also involves the insertion of special flagging operations.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Due to the inherent operator overloading overhead on each loop, this approach usually demonstrates weaker speed performance.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Overloaded Operators can be used to extract the valuation graph, followed by automatic generation of the AD-version of the primal function at run-time.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Unlike the classic OO AAD, such AD-function does not change from one iteration to the next one.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] Hence there is any OO or tape interpretation run-time overhead per Xi sample.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] With the AD-function being generated at runtime, it can be optimised to take into account the current state of the program and precompute certain values.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] In addition, it can be generated in a way to consistently utilize native CPU vectorization to process 4(8)-double chunks of user data (AVX2\AVX512 speed up x4-x8).
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] With multithreading added into account, such approach can lead to a final acceleration of order 8 × #Cores compared to the traditional AAD tools.
[src:dex-language/automatic-differentiation] A reference implementation is available on GitHub.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] A data parallel job on an array of *n* elements can be divided equally among all the processors.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Let us assume we want to sum all the elements of the given array and the time for a single addition operation is Ta time units.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] In the case of sequential execution, the time taken by the process will be *n*×Ta time units as it sums up all the elements of an array.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] On the other hand, if we execute this job as a data parallel job on 4 processors the time taken would reduce to (*n*/4)×Ta + merging overhead time units.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Parallel execution results in a speedup of 4 over sequential execution.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] The locality of data references plays an important part in evaluating the performance of a data parallel programming model.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Locality of data depends on the memory accesses performed by the program as well as the size of the cache.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Exploitation of the concept of data parallelism started in 1960s with the development of the Solomon machine.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] The Solomon machine, also called a vector processor, was developed to expedite the performance of mathematical operations by working on a large data array (operating on multiple data in consecutive time steps).
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Concurrency of data operations was also exploited by operating on multiple data at the same time using a single instruction.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] These processors were called 'array processors'.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] In the 1980s, the term was introduced to describe this programming style, which was widely used to program Connection Machines in data parallel languages like C*.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Today, data parallelism is best exemplified in graphics processing units (GPUs), which use both the techniques of operating on multiple data in space and time using a single instruction.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Most data parallel hardware supports only a fixed number of parallel levels, often only one.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] This means that within a parallel operation it is not possible to launch more parallel operations recursively, and means that programmers cannot make use of nested hardware parallelism.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] The programming language NESL was an early effort at implementing a nested data-parallel programming model on flat parallel machines, and in particular introduced the flattening transformation that transforms nested data parallelism to flat data parallelism.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] This work was continued by other languages such as Data Parallel Haskell and Futhark, although arbitrary nested data parallelism is not widely available in current data-parallel programming languages.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] In a multiprocessor system executing a single set of instructions (SIMD), data parallelism is achieved when each processor performs the same task on different distributed data.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] In some situations, a single execution thread controls operations on all the data.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] In others, different threads control the operation, but they execute the same code.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] For instance, consider matrix multiplication and addition in a sequential manner as discussed in the example.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Below is the sequential pseudo-code for multiplication and addition of two matrices where the result is stored in the matrix *C*.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] The pseudo-code for multiplication calculates the dot product of two matrices *A*, *B* and stores the result into the output matrix *C*.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] If the following programs were executed sequentially, the time taken to calculate the result would be of the $O(n^{3})$ (assuming row lengths and column lengths of both matrices are n) and $O(n)$ for multiplication and addition respectively.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] We can exploit data parallelism in the preceding code to execute it faster as the arithmetic is loop independent.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Parallelization of the matrix multiplication code is achieved by using OpenMP.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] An OpenMP directive, "omp parallel for" instructs the compiler to execute the code in the for loop in parallel.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] For multiplication, we can divide matrix A and B into blocks along rows and columns respectively.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] This allows us to calculate every element in matrix C individually thereby making the task parallel.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] For example: *A[m x n] dot B [n x k]* can be finished in $O(n)$ instead of $O(m*n*k)$ when executed in parallel using *m*k* processors.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] It can be observed from the example that a lot of processors will be required as the matrix sizes keep on increasing.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Keeping the execution time low is the priority but as the matrix size increases, we are faced with other constraints like complexity of such a system and its associated costs.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Therefore, constraining the number of processors in the system, we can still apply the same principle and divide the data into bigger chunks to calculate the product of two matrices.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] For addition of arrays in a data parallel implementation, let's assume a more modest system with two central processing units (CPU) A and B, CPU A could add all elements from the top half of the arrays, while CPU B could add all elements from the bottom half of the arrays.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Since the two processors work in parallel, the job of performing array addition would take one half the time of performing the same operation in serial using one CPU alone.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] In an SPMD system executed on 2 processor system, both CPUs will execute the code.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Data parallelism emphasizes the distributed (parallel) nature of the data, as opposed to the processing (task parallelism).
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Most real programs fall somewhere on a continuum between task parallelism and data parallelism.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] The process of parallelizing a sequential program can be broken down into four discrete steps.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Data and task parallelism, can be simultaneously implemented by combining them together for the same application.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] This is called Mixed data and task parallelism.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Mixed parallelism requires sophisticated scheduling algorithms and software support.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] It is the best kind of parallelism when communication is slow and number of processors is large.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Mixed data and task parallelism has many applications.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] The data is divided among different sub-circuits and parallelism is achieved with orchestration from the tasks.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] OpenMP: It's an Application Programming Interface (API) which supports shared memory programming models on multiple platforms of multiprocessor systems.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Since version 4.5, OpenMP is also able to target devices other than typical CPUs.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] It can program FPGAs, DSPs, GPUs and more.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] It is not confined to GPUs like OpenACC.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] CUDA and OpenACC: CUDA and OpenACC (respectively) are parallel computing API platforms designed to allow a software engineer to utilize GPUs' computational units for general purpose processing.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Threading Building Blocks and RaftLib: Both open source programming environments that enable mixed data/task parallelism in C/C++ environments across heterogeneous resources.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Data parallelism finds its applications in a variety of fields ranging from physics, chemistry, biology, material sciences to signal processing.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Sciences imply data parallelism for simulating models like molecular dynamics, sequence analysis of genome data and other physical phenomenon.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Driving forces in signal processing for data parallelism are video encoding, image and graphics processing, wireless communications to name a few.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Data-intensive computing is a class of parallel computing applications which use a data parallel approach to process large volumes of data typically terabytes or petabytes in size and typically referred to as big data.
[src:dex-language/data-parallelism] Computing applications that devote most of their execution time to computational requirements are deemed compute-intensive, whereas applications are deemed data-intensive if they require large volumes of data and devote most of their processing time to input/output and manipulation of data.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Essentially, a GPGPU pipeline is a kind of parallel processing between one or more GPUs and CPUs, with special accelerated instructions for processing image or other graphic forms of data.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While GPUs operate at lower frequencies, they typically have many times the number of processing elements.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Thus, GPUs can process far more pictures and other graphical data per second than a traditional CPU.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Migrating data into parallel form and then using the GPU to process it can (theoretically) create a large speedup.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines were developed at the beginning of the 21st century for graphics processing (e.g. for better shaders).
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] From the history of supercomputing it is well-known that scientific computing drives the largest concentrations of Computing power in history, listed in the TOP500: the majority today utilize GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The best-known GPGPUs are Nvidia Tesla that are used for Nvidia DGX, alongside AMD Instinct and Intel Gaudi.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In principle, any arbitrary Boolean function, including addition, multiplication, and other mathematical functions, can be built up from a functionally complete set of logic operators.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In 1987, Conway's Game of Life became one of the first examples of general-purpose computing using an early stream processor called a blitter to invoke a special sequence of logical operations on bit vectors.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] General-purpose computing on GPUs became more practical and popular after about 2001, with the advent of both programmable shaders and floating point support on graphics processors.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Notably, problems involving matrices and/or vectors – especially two-, three-, or four-dimensional vectors – were easy to translate to a GPU, which acts with native speed and support on those types.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A significant milestone for GPGPU was the year 2003 when two research groups independently discovered GPU-based approaches for the solution of general linear algebra problems on GPUs that ran faster than on CPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These early efforts to use GPUs as general-purpose processors required reformulating computational problems in terms of graphics primitives, as supported by the two major APIs for graphics processors, OpenGL and Direct3D.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This cumbersome translation was obviated by the advent of general-purpose programming languages and APIs such as Sh/RapidMind, Brook and Accelerator.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] These were followed by Nvidia's CUDA, which allowed programmers to ignore the underlying graphical concepts in favor of more common high-performance computing concepts.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Newer, hardware-vendor-independent offerings include Microsoft's DirectCompute and Apple/Khronos Group's OpenCL.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This means that modern GPGPU pipelines can leverage the speed of a GPU without requiring full and explicit conversion of the data to a graphical form.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mark Harris, the founder of GPGPU.org, claims he coined the term *GPGPU*.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Any language that allows the code running on the CPU to poll a GPU shader for return values, can create a GPGPU framework.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programming standards for parallel computing include OpenCL (vendor-independent), OpenACC, OpenMP and OpenHMPP.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As of 2016, OpenCL is the dominant open general-purpose GPU computing language, and is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL provides a cross-platform GPGPU platform that additionally supports data parallel compute on CPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is actively supported on Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM platforms.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The Khronos Group has also standardised and implemented SYCL, a higher-level programming model for OpenCL as a single-source domain specific embedded language based on pure C++11.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The dominant proprietary framework is Nvidia CUDA.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia launched CUDA in 2006, a software development kit (SDK) and application programming interface (API) that allows using the programming language C to code algorithms for execution on GeForce 8 series and later GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ROCm, launched in 2016, is AMD's open-source response to CUDA.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is, as of 2022, on par with CUDA with regards to features, and still lacking in consumer support.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenVIDIA was developed at University of Toronto between 2003–2005, in collaboration with Nvidia.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Altimesh Hybridizer created by Altimesh compiles Common Intermediate Language to CUDA binaries.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It supports generics and virtual functions.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Debugging and profiling is integrated with Visual Studio and Nsight.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is available as a Visual Studio extension on Visual Studio Marketplace.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced the DirectCompute GPU computing API, released with the Direct3D 11 API.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] MATLAB supports GPGPU acceleration using the *Parallel Computing Toolbox* and *MATLAB Distributed Computing Server*, and third-party packages like Jacket.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU processing is also used to simulate Newtonian physics by physics engines, and commercial implementations include Havok Physics, FX and PhysX, both of which are typically used for computer and video games.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] C++ Accelerated Massive Parallelism (C++ AMP) is a library that accelerates execution of C++ code by exploiting the data-parallel hardware on GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to a trend of increasing power of mobile GPUs, general-purpose programming became available also on the mobile devices running major mobile operating systems.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Google Android 4.2 enabled running RenderScript code on the mobile device GPU.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] RenderScript has since been deprecated in favour of first OpenGL compute shaders and later Vulkan Compute.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] OpenCL is available on many Android devices, but is not officially supported by Android.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Apple introduced the proprietary Metal API for iOS applications, able to execute arbitrary code through Apple's GPU compute shaders.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Originally, data was simply passed one-way from a central processing unit (CPU) to a graphics processing unit (GPU), then to a display device.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] As time progressed, however, it became valuable for GPUs to store at first simple, then complex structures of data to be passed back to the CPU that analyzed an image, or a set of scientific-data represented as a 2D or 3D format that a video card can understand.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Transferring the portion of the data set to be actively analyzed to that GPU memory in the form of textures or other easily readable GPU forms results in speed increase.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The distinguishing feature of a GPGPU design is the ability to transfer information bidirectionally back from the GPU to the CPU; generally the data throughput in both directions is ideally high, resulting in a multiplier effect on the speed of a specific high-use algorithm.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU pipelines may improve efficiency on especially large data sets and/or data containing 2D or 3D imagery.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is used in complex graphics pipelines as well as scientific computing; more so in fields with large data sets like genome mapping, or where two- or three-dimensional analysis is useful – especially at present biomolecule analysis, protein study, and other complex organic chemistry.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An example of such applications is NVIDIA software suite for genome analysis.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such pipelines can also vastly improve efficiency in image processing and computer vision, among other fields; as well as parallel processing generally.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some very heavily optimized pipelines have yielded speed increases of several hundred times the original CPU-based pipeline on one high-use task.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example would be a GPU program that collects data about average lighting values as it renders some view from either a camera or a computer graphics program back to the main program on the CPU, so that the CPU can then make adjustments to the overall screen view.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A more advanced example might use edge detection to return both numerical information and a processed image representing outlines to a computer vision program controlling, say, a mobile robot.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPGPU as a software concept is a type of algorithm, not a piece of equipment.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Specialized equipment designs may, however, even further enhance the efficiency of GPGPU pipelines, which traditionally perform relatively few algorithms on very large amounts of data.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Massively parallelized, gigantic-data-level tasks thus may be parallelized even further via specialized setups such as rack computing (many similar, highly tailored machines built into a *rack*), which adds a third layer – many computing units each using many CPUs to correspond to many GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some Bitcoin "miners" used such setups for high-quantity processing.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Insights into the largest such systems in the world has been maintained at the TOP500 supercomputer list.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Historically, CPUs have used hardware-managed caches, but the earlier GPUs only provided software-managed local memories.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, as GPUs are being increasingly used for general-purpose applications, state-of-the-art GPUs are being designed with hardware-managed multi-level caches which have helped the GPUs to move towards mainstream computing.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, GeForce 200 series GT200 architecture GPUs did not feature an L2 cache, the Fermi GPU has 768 KiB last-level cache, the Kepler GPU has 1.5 MiB last-level cache, the Maxwell GPU has 2 MiB last-level cache, and the Pascal GPU has 4 MiB last-level cache.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs have very large register files, which allow them to reduce context-switching latency.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Register file size is also increasing over different GPU generations, e.g., the total register file size on Maxwell (GM200), Pascal and Volta GPUs are 6 MiB, 14 MiB and 20 MiB, respectively.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] By comparison, the size of a register file on CPUs is small, typically tens or hundreds of kilobytes.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In essence: almost all GPU workloads are inherently massively-parallel LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE in nature, such as tiled rendering.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Even storing one temporary vector for further recall (LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE-COMPUTE-LOAD-COMPUTE-STORE) is so expensive due to the memory wall problem that it is to be avoided at all costs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result is that register file size *has* to increase.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In standard CPUs it is possible to introduce caches (a D-cache) to solve this problem, however these are relativrly so large that they are impractical to introduce in GPUs which would need one per processing element.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ILLIAC IV innovatively solved the problem around 1967 by introducing a local memory per processing element (a PEM): a strategy copied by the Aspex ASP.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Much like how CPUs may elect to implement wider vector instructions in smaller pieces (e.g.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] AMD Bulldozer supported the 256-bit AVX instructions by splitting them into two 128-bit operations) to save power and/or chip area, GPU designers also vary the amount of execution units to fit their expected workloads.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On a GPGPU, each of the following resources can vary freely in ratio from the others: FP64 (FMA), FP32 (FMA), FP16 (FMA), Int32 Add, Int32 Mul, RCP/RSQRT.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] (An example can be seen in Nvidia's documentation about the execution resources found in each SM of different generation (compute capacity) of GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is therefore insufficient to simply qualify a GPU's computational capabilities in terms of FLOPS: FLOPS values should be separately presented for matrix vs non-matrix modes and (T)OPS figures should also be presented for integer operations.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The high performance of GPUs comes at the cost of high power consumption, which under full load is in fact as much power as the rest of the PC system combined.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The maximum power consumption of the Pascal series GPU (Tesla P100) was specified to be 250W.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In terms of raw computing power (FLOPS, TOPS, etc.), GPUs tend to have more performance-per-watt than a typical CPU.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, it takes a well-written program and a fitting workload to extract most of this power, as most of the time (and power) would otherwise be wasted on local and host memory access.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Before CUDA was published in 2007, GPGPU was "classical" and involved repurposing graphics primitives.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] More examples are available in part 4 of *GPU Gems 2*.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Using GPU for numerical linear algebra began at least in 2001.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It had been used for Gauss-Seidel solver, conjugate gradients, etc.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Computer video cards are produced by various vendors, such as Nvidia, AMD.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Cards from such vendors differ on implementing data-format support, such as integer and floating-point formats (32-bit and 64-bit).
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Microsoft introduced a *Shader Model* standard, to help rank the various features of graphic cards into a simple Shader Model version number (1.0, 2.0, 3.0, etc.).
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Pre-Direct3D 9 video cards only supported paletted or integer color types.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Sometimes another alpha value is added, to be used for transparency.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For early fixed-function or limited programmability graphics (i.e., up to and including Direct3D 8.1-compliant GPUs) this was sufficient because this is also the representation used in displays.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This representation does have certain limitations.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Given sufficient graphics processing power even graphics programmers would like to use better formats, such as floating point data formats, to obtain effects such as high-dynamic-range imaging.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many GPGPU applications require floating point accuracy, which came with video cards conforming to the Direct3D 9 specification.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Direct3D 9 Shader Model 2.x suggested the support of two precision types: full and partial precision.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Full precision support could either be FP32 or FP24 (floating point 32- or 24-bit per component) or greater, while partial precision was FP16.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] ATI's Radeon R300 series of GPUs supported FP24 precision only in the programmable fragment pipeline (although FP32 was supported in the vertex processors) while Nvidia's NV30 series supported both FP16 and FP32; other vendors such as S3 Graphics and XGI supported a mixture of formats up to FP24.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The implementations of floating point on Nvidia GPUs are mostly IEEE compliant; however, this is not true across all vendors.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This has implications for correctness which are considered important to some scientific applications.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While 64-bit floating point values (double precision float) are commonly available on CPUs, these are not universally supported on GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some GPU architectures sacrifice IEEE compliance, while others lack double-precision.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Efforts have occurred to emulate double-precision floating point values on GPUs; however, the speed tradeoff negates any benefit to offloading the computing onto the GPU in the first place.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Most operations on the GPU operate in a vectorized fashion: one operation can be performed on up to four values at once.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For example, if one color ⟨R1, G1, B1⟩ is to be modulated by another color ⟨R2, G2, B2⟩, the GPU can produce the resulting color ⟨R1*R2, G1*G2, B1*B2⟩ in one operation.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This functionality is useful in graphics because almost every basic data type is a vector (either 2-, 3-, or 4-dimensional).
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Examples include vertices, colors, normal vectors, and texture coordinates.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] GPUs are originally designed specifically for graphics and thus are very restrictive in operations and programming.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Due to their design, GPUs are only effective for problems that can be solved using stream processing and the hardware can only be used in certain ways.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the early GPGPU age, GPUs can only process independent vertices and fragments, but can process many of them in parallel.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is especially effective when the programmer wants to process many vertices or fragments in the same way.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In this sense, GPUs are stream processors – processors that can operate in parallel by running one kernel on many records in a stream at once.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Programmers would use graphics APIs (OpenGL or Direct3D) to perform general-purpose computation.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] With the introduction of the CUDA (Nvidia, 2007) and OpenCL (vendor-independent, 2008) general-purpose computing APIs, in new GPGPU codes it is no longer necessary to map the computation to graphics primitives.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The stream processing nature of GPUs remains valid regardless of the APIs used.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A *stream* is simply a set of records that require similar computation.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] *Kernels* are the functions that are applied to each element in the stream.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In the GPUs, *vertices* and *fragments* are the elements in streams and vertex and fragment shaders are the kernels to be run on them.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For each element we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Arithmetic intensity is defined as the number of operations performed per word of memory transferred.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] It is important for GPGPU applications to have high arithmetic intensity else the memory access latency will limit computational speedup.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Ideal GPGPU applications have large data sets, high parallelism, and minimal dependency between data elements.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In fact, a program can substitute a write only texture for output instead of the framebuffer.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is done either through render-to-texture (RTT), render-to-backbuffer-copy-to-texture (RTBCTT), or the more recent stream-out.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common form for a stream to take in GPGPU is a 2D grid because this fits naturally with the rendering model built into GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Many computations naturally map into grids: matrix algebra, image processing, physically based simulation, and so on.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Since textures are used as memory, texture lookups are then used as memory reads.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Certain operations can be done automatically by the GPU because of this.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Compute kernels can be thought of as the body of loops.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] On the GPU, the programmer only specifies the body of the loop as the kernel and what data to loop over by invoking geometry processing.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] For accurate technical information on this topic see Predication_(computer_architecture)#SIMD,_SIMT_and_vector_predication and ILLIAC IV "branching" (the term "predicate mask" did not exist in 1967).
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In sequential code it is possible to control the flow of the program using if-then-else statements and various forms of loops.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Such flow control structures have only recently been added to GPUs.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Conditional writes could be performed using a properly crafted series of arithmetic/bit operations, but looping and conditional branching were not possible.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Recent GPUs allow branching, but usually with a performance penalty.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Branching should generally be avoided in inner loops, whether in CPU or GPU code, and various methods, such as static branch resolution, pre-computation, predication, loop splitting, and Z-cull can be used to achieve branching when hardware support does not exist.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation simply applies the given function (the kernel) to every element in the stream.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A simple example is multiplying each value in the stream by a constant (increasing the brightness of an image).
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The map operation is simple to implement on the GPU.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The programmer generates a fragment for each pixel on screen and applies a fragment program to each one.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The result stream of the same size is stored in the output buffer.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Some computations require calculating a smaller stream (possibly a stream of only one element) from a larger stream.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] This is called a reduction of the stream.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Generally, a reduction can be performed in multiple steps.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The results from the prior step are used as the input for the current step and the range over which the operation is applied is reduced until only one stream element remains.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Stream filtering is essentially a non-uniform reduction.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Filtering involves removing items from the stream based on some criteria.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation, also termed *parallel prefix sum*, takes in a vector (stream) of data elements and an (arbitrary) associative binary function '+' with an identity element 'i'.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] If the input is [a0, a1, a2, a3, ...], an *exclusive scan* produces the output [i, a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, ...], while an *inclusive scan* produces the output [a0, a0 + a1, a0 + a1 + a2, a0 + a1 + a2 + a3, ...] and does not require an identity to exist.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] While at first glance the operation may seem inherently serial, efficient parallel scan algorithms are possible and have been implemented on graphics processing units.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scan operation has uses in e.g., quicksort and sparse matrix-vector multiplication.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The scatter operation is most naturally defined on the vertex processor.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The vertex processor is able to adjust the position of the vertex, which allows the programmer to control where information is deposited on the grid.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Other extensions are also possible, such as controlling how large an area the vertex affects.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The fragment processor cannot perform a direct scatter operation because the location of each fragment on the grid is fixed at the time of the fragment's creation and cannot be altered by the programmer.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] However, a logical scatter operation may sometimes be recast or implemented with another gather step.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] A scatter implementation would first emit both an output value and an output address.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] An immediately following gather operation uses address comparisons to see whether the output value maps to the current output slot.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, scatter can be performed by indexed writes.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] After scatter reorders elements according to a map, gather can restore the order of the elements according to the map scatter used.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In dedicated compute kernels, gather may be performed by indexed reads.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] In other shaders, it is performed with texture-lookups.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The sort operation transforms an unordered set of elements into an ordered set of elements.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The most common implementation on GPUs is using radix sort for integer and floating point data and coarse-grained merge sort and fine-grained sorting networks for general comparable data.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] The search operation allows the programmer to find a given element within the stream, or possibly find neighbors of a specified element.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Mostly the search method used is binary search on sorted elements.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Nvidia recommended GPUs for this application.
[src:dex-language/general-purpose-computing-on-graphics-processing-units] Check with developer or ISV to obtain certification information.
[src:dex-language/gpu] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:dex-language/gpu] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:dex-language/gpu] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:dex-language/gpu] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:dex-language/gpu] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:dex-language/gpu] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:dex-language/gpu] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:dex-language/gpu] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:dex-language/gpu] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:dex-language/gpu] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:dex-language/gpu] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:dex-language/gpu] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:dex-language/gpu] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:dex-language/gpu] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:dex-language/gpu] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:dex-language/gpu] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:dex-language/gpu] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:dex-language/gpu] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:dex-language/gpu] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:dex-language/gpu] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:dex-language/gpu] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:dex-language/gpu] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:dex-language/gpu] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:dex-language/gpu] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:dex-language/gpu] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:dex-language/gpu] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:dex-language/gpu] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:dex-language/gpu] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:dex-language/gpu] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:dex-language/gpu] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:dex-language/gpu] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:dex-language/gpu] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:dex-language/gpu] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:dex-language/gpu] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:dex-language/gpu] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:dex-language/gpu] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:dex-language/gpu] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:dex-language/gpu] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a combination of the two traditional approaches to translation to machine code: ahead-of-time compilation (AOT), and interpretation, which combines some advantages and drawbacks of both.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Roughly, JIT compilation combines the speed of compiled code with the flexibility of interpretation, with the overhead of an interpreter and the additional overhead of compiling and linking (not just interpreting).
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is a form of dynamic compilation, and allows adaptive optimization such as dynamic recompilation and microarchitecture-specific speedups.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Interpretation and JIT compilation are particularly suited for dynamic programming languages, as the runtime system can handle late-bound data types and enforce security guarantees.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The earliest published JIT compiler is generally attributed to work on LISP by John McCarthy in 1960.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Another early example was by Ken Thompson, who in 1968 gave one of the first applications of regular expressions, here for pattern matching in the text editor QED.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] For speed, Thompson implemented regular expression matching by JITing to IBM 7094 code on the Compatible Time-Sharing System.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] An influential technique for deriving compiled code from interpretation was pioneered by James G.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Mitchell in 1970, which he implemented for the experimental language *LC²*.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] 1980) pioneered new aspects of JIT compilations.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] For example, translation to machine code was done on demand, and the result was cached for later use.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] When memory became scarce, the system would delete some of this code and regenerate it when it was needed again.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Sun's Self language improved these techniques extensively and was at one point the fastest Smalltalk system in the world, achieving up to half the speed of optimized C but with a fully object-oriented programming language.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Self was abandoned by Sun, but the research went into the Java language.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The term "Just-in-time compilation" was borrowed from the manufacturing term "Just in time" and popularized by Java, with James Gosling using the term from 1993.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Currently JITing is used by most implementations of the Java virtual machine, as HotSpot builds on, and extensively uses, this research base.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The HP project Dynamo was an experimental JIT compiler where the "bytecode" format and the machine code format were the same; the system optimized PA-8000 machine code.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In November 2020, PHP 8.0 introduced a JIT compiler.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In October 2024, CPython introduced an experimental JIT compiler.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In a bytecode-compiled system, source code is translated to an intermediate representation known as bytecode.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Bytecode is not the machine code for any particular computer, and may be portable among computer architectures.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The bytecode may then be interpreted by, or run on a virtual machine.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The JIT compiler reads the bytecodes in many sections (or in full, rarely) and compiles them dynamically into machine code so the program can run faster.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] This can be done per-file, per-function or even on any arbitrary code fragment; the code can be compiled when it is about to be executed (hence the name "just-in-time"), and then cached and reused later without needing to be recompiled.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] By contrast, a traditional *interpreted virtual machine* will simply interpret the bytecode, generally with much lower performance.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Some *interpreter*s even interpret source code, without the step of first compiling to bytecode, with even worse performance.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] *Statically-compiled code* or *native code* is compiled prior to deployment.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] A *dynamic compilation environment* is one in which the compiler can be used during execution.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The deployed bytecode is portable, unlike native code.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Since the runtime has control over the compilation, like interpreted bytecode, it can run in a secure sandbox.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Compilers from bytecode to machine code are easier to write, because the portable bytecode compiler has already done much of the work.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT code generally offers far better performance than interpreters.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The system is able to collect statistics about how the program is actually running in the environment it is in, and it can rearrange and recompile for optimum performance.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] However, some static compilers can also take profile information as input.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The system can do global code optimizations (e.g. inlining of library functions) without losing the advantages of dynamic linking and without the overheads inherent to static compilers and linkers.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] With just-in-time compilation in many cases this processing can be moved out of loops, often giving large increases of speed.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Although this is possible with statically compiled garbage collected languages, a bytecode system can more easily rearrange executed code for better cache utilization.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] However, a special type of "JIT" may potentially *not* target the physical machine's CPU architecture, but rather an optimized VM bytecode where limitations on raw machine code prevail, especially where that bytecode's VM eventually leverages a JIT to native code.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT causes a slight to noticeable delay in the initial execution of an application, due to the time taken to load and compile the input code.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Sometimes this delay is called "startup time delay" or "warm-up time".
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In general, the more optimization JIT performs, the better the code it will generate, but the initial delay will also increase.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] A JIT compiler therefore has to make a trade-off between the compilation time and the quality of the code it hopes to generate.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Startup time can include increased IO-bound operations in addition to JIT compilation: for example, the *rt.jar* class data file for the Java virtual machine (JVM) is 40 MB and the JVM must seek a lot of data in this contextually huge file.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] One possible optimization, used by Sun's HotSpot Java virtual machine, is to combine interpretation and JIT compilation.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The application code is initially interpreted, but the JVM monitors which sequences of bytecode are frequently executed and translates them to machine code for direct execution on the hardware.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] For bytecode which is executed only a few times, this saves the compilation time and reduces the initial latency; for frequently executed bytecode, JIT compilation is used to run at high speed, after an initial phase of slow interpretation.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Further, since a program spends most time executing a minority of its code, the reduced compilation time is significant.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Finally, during the initial code interpretation, execution statistics can be collected before compilation, which helps to perform better optimization.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] The correct tradeoff can vary due to circumstances.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] For example, Sun's Java virtual machine has two major modes—client and server.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In client mode, minimal compilation and optimization is performed, to reduce startup time.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In server mode, extensive compilation and optimization is performed, to maximize performance once the application is running by sacrificing startup time.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Other Java just-in-time compilers have used a runtime measurement of the number of times a method has executed combined with the bytecode size of a method as a heuristic to decide when to compile.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Still another uses the number of times executed combined with the detection of loops.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In general, it is much harder to accurately predict which methods to optimize in short-running applications than in long-running ones.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Native Image Generator (Ngen) by Microsoft is another approach at reducing the initial delay.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Ngen pre-compiles (or "pre-JITs") bytecode in a Common Intermediate Language image into machine native code.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] As a result, no runtime compilation is needed. .NET Framework 2.0 shipped with Visual Studio 2005 runs Ngen on all of the Microsoft dynamic-link library (DLL) files right after installing.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Pre-jitting provides a way to reduce startup time.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] However, the quality of code it generates may be lower than the one that is JITed, for the same reasons why code compiled statically, without profile-guided optimization, cannot be as good as JIT compiled code in the extreme case: the lack of profiling data to drive, for instance, inline caching.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] There also exist Java implementations that combine an AOT (ahead-of-time) compiler with either a JIT compiler (Excelsior JET) or interpreter (GNU Compiler for Java).
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation may not reliably achieve its goal, namely entering a steady state of improved performance after a short initial warmup period.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Across eight different virtual machines, Barrett et al.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] (2017) measured six widely used microbenchmarks which are commonly used by virtual machine implementors as optimisation targets, running them repeatedly within a single process execution.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Even where an improved steady-state was reached, it sometimes took many hundreds of iterations.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] (2022) instead focused on the HotSpot virtual machine but with a much wider array of benchmarks, finding that 10.9% of process executions failed to reach a steady state of performance, and 43.5% of benchmarks did not consistently attain a steady state across multiple executions.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation fundamentally uses executable data, and thus poses security challenges and possible exploits.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Implementation of JIT compilation consists of compiling source code or byte code to machine code and executing it.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] This is generally done directly in memory: the JIT compiler outputs the machine code directly into memory and immediately executes it, rather than outputting it to disk and then invoking the code as a separate program, as in usual ahead of time compilation.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] In modern architectures this runs into a problem due to executable space protection: arbitrary memory cannot be executed, as otherwise there is a potential security hole.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Thus memory must be marked as executable; for security reasons this should be done *after* the code has been written to memory, and marked read-only, as writable/executable memory is a security hole (see W^X).
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] For instance Firefox's JIT compiler for JavaScript introduced this protection in a release version with Firefox 46.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT spraying is a class of computer security exploits that use JIT compilation for heap spraying: the resulting memory is then executable, which allows an exploit if execution can be moved into the heap.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation can be applied to some programs, or can be used for certain capacities, particularly dynamic capacities such as regular expressions.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] For example, a text editor may compile a regular expression provided at runtime to machine code to allow faster matching: this cannot be done ahead of time, as the pattern is only provided at runtime.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Several modern runtime environments rely on JIT compilation for high-speed code execution, including most implementations of Java, together with Microsoft's .NET.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Similarly, many regular-expression libraries feature JIT compilation of regular expressions, either to bytecode or to machine code.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilation is also used in some emulators, in order to translate machine code from one CPU architecture to another.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] A common implementation of JIT compilation is to first have AOT compilation to bytecode (virtual machine code), known as *bytecode compilation*, and then have JIT compilation to machine code (dynamic compilation), rather than interpretation of the bytecode.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] This improves the runtime performance compared to interpretation, at the cost of lag due to compilation.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] JIT compilers translate continuously, as with interpreters, but caching of compiled code minimizes lag on future execution of the same code during a given run.
[src:dex-language/just-in-time-compilation] Since only part of the program is compiled, there is significantly less lag than if the entire program were compiled prior to execution.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:dex-language/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:dex-language/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:dex-language/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:dex-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
